    epicHistory: `
There were eight houses. The histories, burned and rewritten by the seven who survived, will tell you otherwise — but the groves remember. The groves always remember.

House Viridane was the youngest of the noble families, the last to be elevated before the sun began its slow, final dimming. Their seat was in the Frostwood Reach, among the ancient ironwood forests that had stood since before the first human set foot on the continent. When the Keth-Amar descended to devour the dying sun and the noble families met to decide what could be done, Viridane argued for resistance — for ritual, for war, for anything other than the Warden's proposed terms. They were outvoted. The seven older houses, desperate and terrified, agreed to the bargain: the sun would be buried beneath the earth, its heat released through volcanic fissures, and in exchange, the firstborn of every noble bloodline would be marched to the northern peaks and consumed.

House Viridane refused. Not publicly — they attended the councils, voted their dissent, and then, on the night before the sacrifice, gathered every child, every servant, every sworn knight who would follow them, and fled south through the Frostwood Reach. They were not pursued by the Warden's frost-hounds. They were pursued by something worse: the knowledge that the seven families would never forgive the refusal, and that survival would require a counter-bargain of equal weight.

In the moonlit groves — ancient hollows where the protective fog thins and the old laws still hold — they found the fae. The fae offered protection, but the terms were absolute: wear your word in your flesh, let the grove anchor your memories against the mist, and never write down what you wish to preserve. The Briaran accepted. The thorns grew.

The seven families, meanwhile, began the erasure. It was not enough that Viridane had refused — the refusal had to be made impossible to remember. Three generations of dedicated mages scoured the name from every book, every treaty, every genealogical scroll. The Viridane sigils were pried from stone lintels. The Viridane dead were exhumed and reburied under blank markers. The Viridane living were declared a myth, a fever-dream, a lie told by peasants who had seen thorns on a stranger's arm and invented a noble house to explain them.

The story the seven families seeded — and that has seeped into every kingdom's understanding — is that House Viridane's cowardice weakened the Warden's bargain, and the world's slow death by the Warden's hunger is their fault. This is the Oathbreaker's Stain: a lie told so often and so thoroughly that it has become the accepted history of every culture that trades with the old noble houses. The Hrym believe it. The Emberth have been taught it. The Mimir, who know what it means to be erased, are the only race that openly doubts it — and even they are not sure.

The Briaran have survived for eight centuries in the spaces between official records. They do not appear in census counts. They do not appear in trade agreements. They are occasionally documented by scholars who later recant, by explorers who later vanish, by bounty hunters who later decide — inexplicably — to retire. The Unshorn hold the deep groves. The Smooth-Skinned walk the wider world in borrowed names. Both carry the same wound: an ancestor abandoned during the flight south, a promise made to someone who was left behind and never seen again. Every Briaran bloodline still carries that promise. Every Briaran's thorns still drift toward it.
    `,

