    currentCrisis: `
The oral history is dying. Not the tradition itself — the Unshorn still recite, the Smooth-Skinned still whisper their fragments in the dark. But the elders who carry the oldest layers of the spoken archive are dying faster than the young can memorize, and every death takes irreplaceable knowledge into the mist. The Unshorn, deep in the groves, are down to four elders who can recite the full lineage from Isane to the present. The youngest of them is ninety-three. The oldest has begun to forget which century she is speaking from.

Meanwhile, the seven families — or what remains of them — have noticed something. A young noble scholar in the eastern kingdoms published a monograph last year arguing that the standard history of House Viridane's "cowardice" contains chronological inconsistencies that suggest the story was retroactively inserted into records that predate the Warden's bargain. The monograph was suppressed within a month. The scholar has disappeared. But copies are circulating, and the Briaran who have gotten hold of one are asking questions that make the elders very afraid.

The Smooth-Skinned report increased noble activity near the groves — not the Hunters who pursue the Mimir for their masks, but scholars, surveyors, cartographers, people asking careful questions about "local folklore" and "oral traditions." The seven houses are not hunting the Briaran openly. They are doing something more dangerous: they are preparing to acknowledge that the Briaran exist, and when they do, it will be on their terms — a revision of the revision, a new story that explains away the erasure without admitting the crime.

The Unshorn want to preempt this by sending emissaries to the other races — to the Mimir, who know what erasure feels like, to the Myrathil, who have no stake in the noble houses' politics, to anyone who might believe the truth before the seven families rewrite it again. The Smooth-Skinned think this is suicide — visibility invites extinction. The argument is not new. It has been going on for eight centuries. But for the first time, the argument has a deadline.
    `,

    culturalPractices: `
Every Briaran child, whether Unshorn or Smooth-Skinned, learns the First Refusal before they learn to speak in full sentences. It is a single sentence, passed from parent to child in a whisper, never written down: "We are the ones who said no." The child is not told what it means until they are old enough to understand the danger of knowing. Unshorn children learn the full oral history in fragments, each fragment added when the child can recite the previous one perfectly — a process that takes until early adulthood. Smooth-Skinned children learn the fragments in secret, at night, and are taught to never, ever repeat them to anyone whose thorns they cannot feel.

The Thorn-Tithe is the central ritual of Briaran life. Every season, each Briaran collects their shed thorns and returns them to a moonlit grove — the Unshorn at the Thorn-Fall in communal ceremony, the Smooth-Skinned alone and in silence. The tithe is a condition of the fae bargain: the thorns must be returned to the grove that grew them, or the debt accumulates. A Briaran who dies far from a grove leaves their heirs with unrecovered thorns — a debt that manifests as a slow curse on the bloodline, the thorns growing inward, the skin thickening, the connection to the oral history fraying. The Unshorn perform an elaborate ritual to recover the thorns of the distant dead. The Smooth-Skinned who die under false names leave debts their children may never know they owe.

The Naming is the only time a Briaran speaks their true Viridane name aloud to someone who is not Briaran. It is not forbidden — it is simply never done, because speaking the name to an outsider means trusting that outsider with the secret of the bloodline's existence. A Briaran who gives their true name to a non-Briaran is making the most significant promise of their life, and their thorns respond accordingly: a new cluster forms at the throat within days, marking the speaker as someone who has chosen vulnerability over survival. The Unshorn perform the Naming rarely, and only to those who have proven themselves across years. The Smooth-Skinned almost never perform it at all.

Disputes between the Unshorn and the Smooth-Skinned are settled by the Thorn-Reading: both parties present their thorn-clusters to an elder, who reads the patterns of migration and determines, from the physical record of unfinished promises, whose position carries older precedent. The elder's ruling is final because the thorns do not lie — they simply drift toward what is owed. A Briaran whose thorns are clustered at their hands owes a debt of action. A Briaran whose thorns are clustered at their throat owes a debt of speech. A Briaran whose thorns are clustered at their heart owes a debt that has not yet been named, and all parties treat this with reverent, fearful silence.

Death rites are simple and oral. The dying Briaran speaks their last words to whoever is present — no priest, no ritual, just the final addition to the oral history, recorded in memory rather than stone. The body is laid in the deepest available grove, uncovered, with the head facing toward the Hollow-Court. Within days the mist and the soil reclaim it. The thorns do not decay — they remain, a permanent marker, slowly sinking into the earth as new layers of shed accumulate above them. The oldest Briaran graves are deep beneath the Thorn-Fall, invisible from the surface, their thorns still clustered in the patterns of the promises they died carrying.
    `,

